Certainly! Below is an example of how you can create a TikZ diagram to visually represent the two cases \( x \leq \frac{b}{2} \) and \( x > \frac{b}{2} \):

```latex
\documentclass[border=10pt]{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
    % Draw the number line
    \draw[->] (-3,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {$x$};

    % Mark the point b/2
    \node at (2,0.5) [above] {\(\frac{b}{2}\)};
    \fill (2,0) circle (2pt);

    % Left side: x <= b/2
    \draw[dashed, thick] (-3,0) -- (2,0);
    \node at (-1,-0.5) [below] {\( x \leq \frac{b}{2} \)};

    % Right side: x > b/2
    \draw[dashed, thick] (2,0) -- (4,0);
    \node at (3,-0.5) [below] {\( x > \frac{b}{2} \)};

    % Label points
    \node at (-2,-0.5) [below] {\( -3 \)};
    \node at (1,-0.5) [below] {\( 1 \)};
    \node at (3,-0.5) [below] {\( 3 \)};
    \node at (4,-0.5) [below] {\( 4 \)};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code will generate a TikZ diagram with a number line from \(-3\) to \(4\). The point \(\frac{b}{2}\) is marked at \(2\) on the number line. There are dashed lines indicating the intervals for each case:

- The interval \( x \leq \frac{b}{2} \) is shown to the left of \(\frac{b}{2}\).
- The interval \( x > \frac{b}{2} \) is shown to the right of \(\frac{b}{2}\).

